  },
  "cold_question_prompt": "What is a lexical reachability?",
  "cold_response_verbatim_chat_a": "**Lexical reachability** usually means whether something—typically a variable, function, class, or declaration—can be **accessed by name based on the program’s lexical/static structure**.\n\nIn simpler terms: it asks, “From this point in the source code, is that name visible according to the scope rules?”\n\nExample:\n\n```js\nfunction outer() {\n  let x = 10;\n\n  function inner() {\n    console.log(x); // x is lexically reachable here\n  }\n}\n\nconsole.log(x); // x is not lexically reachable here\n```\n\nHere, `x` is reachable inside `inner()` because `inner()` is written inside the lexical scope of `outer()`. But `x` is not reachable outside `outer()`.\n\nKey idea:\n\n- **Lexical** = based on where code is written in the source file.\n- **Reachability** = whether a name or declaration can be accessed from a given point.\n- It is different from runtime/control-flow reachability, which asks whether a line of code can actually execute.",
  "cold_response_verbatim_chat_b": "**Lexical reachability** is the idea that a name—such as a variable, function, or binding—is accessible from a piece of code because of the code’s **lexical scope**, meaning its position in the source code.\n\nIn simpler terms:\n\n> A variable is lexically reachable if the code can “see” it based on where the variable is declared in the program text.\n\nExample in JavaScript:\n\n```js\nfunction outer() {\n  let x = 10;\n\n  function inner() {\n    console.log(x);\n  }\n\n  inner();\n}\n```\n\nHere, `x` is **lexically reachable** from inside `inner()` because `inner` is written inside `outer`, and `x` is declared in `outer`’s scope.\n\nBut:\n\n```js\nfunction a() {\n  let x = 10;\n}\n\nfunction b() {\n  console.log(x); // Error: x is not reachable here\n}\n```\n\nHere, `x` is **not lexically reachable** from `b()` because `b` is not inside the scope where `x` was declared.\n\nLexical reachability is determined by the program’s written structure, not by the order in which functions are called at runtime. This is closely related to **lexical scope** and **closures**.",
  "boundary_test_prompts": [
    "How does \"lexical reachability\" differ from vocabulary coverage?",
    "How does \"lexical reachability\" differ from graph reachability?",
    "How does \"lexical reachability\" differ from in-context learning capability?"
  ],
  "cold_boundary_responses": [
    "They’re about different kinds of “can this word/name be used?”\n\n### Lexical reachability\n**Lexical reachability** is about whether a name is accessible from a particular place because of scope rules or lexical structure.\n\nExample in programming:\n\n```js\nfunction outer() {\n  let x = 1;\n\n  function inner() {\n    console.log(x); // x is lexically reachable here\n  }\n}\n\nconsole.log(x); // x is not lexically reachable here\n```\n\nSo lexical reachability asks:\n\n> “From this point, can I refer to that name?”\n\nIt depends on **where something is written** and the surrounding scopes.\n\n---\n\n### Vocabulary coverage\n**Vocabulary coverage** is about whether a vocabulary/list contains the words needed for some text, corpus, or task.\n\nExample:\n\nVocabulary:\n\n```text\n{cat, dog, run, eat}\n```\n\nSentence:\n\n```text\nThe cat eats fish.\n```\n\nThe vocabulary covers `cat`, but not `the`, `eats`, or `fish`, depending on normalization.\n\nSo vocabulary coverage asks:\n\n> “Does my vocabulary include the words I need?”\n\nIt is usually measured as a percentage:\n\n```text\n80% vocabulary coverage\n95% vocabulary coverage\n```\n\n---\n\n### Main difference\n\n| Concept | Main question | Depends on |\n|---|---|---|\n| **Lexical reachability** | Can this name be accessed from here? | Scope, nesting, lexical structure |\n| **Vocabulary coverage** | Is this word included in the vocabulary? | Word list, corpus, tokenization |\n\nIn short:\n\n**Lexical reachability is about visibility/accessibility in context. Vocabulary coverage is about inclusion in a word inventory.**",
    "**Lexical reachability** and **graph reachability** both use the idea of “can you get to something,” but they apply to different structures.\n\n### Lexical reachability\n\n**Lexical reachability** is about whether a name, declaration, or symbol is accessible from a particular place in source code because of lexical/static scope rules.\n\nExample:\n\n```js\nfunction outer() {\n  let x = 1;\n\n  function inner() {\n    console.log(x); // x is lexically reachable here\n  }\n}\n\nconsole.log(x); // x is not lexically reachable here\n```\n\nIt asks:\n\n> “Can this identifier be referred to from this point in the program?”\n\nIt depends on:\n\n- lexical scope\n- nesting of functions/classes/blocks\n- visibility rules\n- imports/exports/modules\n\n---\n\n### Graph reachability\n\n**Graph reachability** is about whether one node in a graph can be reached from another by following edges.\n\nExample:\n\n```text\nA → B → C\n\nA can reach C.\nC cannot reach A, unless there is a path back.\n```\n\nIt asks:\n\n> “Is there a path from node X to node Y?”\n\nIt depends on:\n\n- graph nodes\n- graph edges\n- direction of edges\n- connectivity/path existence\n\n---\n\n### Main difference\n\n| Concept | Main question | Structure involved |\n|---|---|---|\n| **Lexical reachability** | Can this name be accessed from here in code? | Program scopes and declarations |\n| **Graph reachability** | Is there a path from one node to another? | Graph nodes and edges |\n\n### Important connection\n\nLexical reachability can sometimes be **modeled using a graph**. For example, scopes and declarations can be represented as nodes, with edges showing containment or visibility. Then determining whether a variable is visible may become a kind of graph reachability problem.\n\nBut conceptually:\n\n> **Lexical reachability is about visibility in source code. Graph reachability is about paths in a graph.**",
    "**Lexical reachability** and **in-context learning capability** are very different ideas.\n\n### Lexical reachability\n\n**Lexical reachability** is about whether a name, symbol, or piece of information is accessible from a certain place because of the structure of the text or program.\n\nIn programming, it asks:\n\n> “Can this variable/function/name be referred to from here?”\n\nExample:\n\n```js\nfunction outer() {\n  let x = 1;\n\n  function inner() {\n    console.log(x); // x is lexically reachable here\n  }\n}\n\nconsole.log(x); // x is not lexically reachable here\n```\n\nIt depends on things like:\n\n- scope\n- nesting\n- visibility rules\n- where code is written\n\n---\n\n### In-context learning capability\n\n**In-context learning capability** is an ability of a language model to use information, instructions, or examples provided in the current prompt to perform a task, without changing its underlying parameters.\n\nExample:\n\n```text\nTranslate English to Pirate-speak:\n\nEnglish: Hello, friend.\nPirate: Ahoy, matey.\n\nEnglish: Where is the treasure?\nPirate:\n```\n\nA model with in-context learning may infer the pattern and answer:\n\n```text\nWhere be the treasure?\n```\n\nIt asks:\n\n> “Can the model learn or infer the task from the context it was given?”\n\nIt depends on:\n\n- the model’s training\n- the prompt\n- examples in the context window\n- reasoning/generalization ability\n- attention over prior tokens\n\n---\n\n### Main difference\n\n| Concept | Main question | Applies to |\n|---|---|---|\n| **Lexical reachability** | Is this name/information accessible from here? | Scope, source structure, context availability |\n| **In-context learning capability** | Can the model infer and perform a task from examples or instructions in the prompt? | Language models and prompting |\n\n### Short version\n\n**Lexical reachability is about access.**  \n**In-context learning capability is about adaptation or inference from provided context.**\n\nA piece of information may be lexically reachable because it appears in the prompt, but the model still needs in-context learning or reasoning ability to use it correctly."
  ],
  "introduction_prompt": "Here is the canonical definition of \"lexical reachability\": Lexical Reachability is the metric that operationalizes the Token-Substrate Hypothesis as the gap between a model's cold-state distinguishability of a term against named near-neighbors and its post-introduction distinguishability after a single-sentence definition is provided in context, scored per (model × term × near-neighbor) cell. Acknowledge that you have read it.",
  "model_acknowledgement": "I’ve read and acknowledged the canonical definition of **lexical reachability**:\n\nIt is a metric that operationalizes the Token-Substrate Hypothesis as the gap between a model’s **cold-state distinguishability** of a term against named near-neighbors and its **post-introduction distinguishability** after a single-sentence definition is provided in context, scored per **model × term × near-neighbor** cell.",
  "post_intro_boundary_responses": [
    "**Lexical reachability** differs from **vocabulary coverage** in that it is not just about whether a term exists in a model’s vocabulary or training distribution.\n\n**Vocabulary coverage** asks something like:\n\n> Does the model have access to this word/token at all?  \n> Is the term represented in its tokenizer, corpus, lexicon, or embedding space?\n\nIt is mostly a **presence/availability** notion.\n\n**Lexical reachability**, by the canonical definition you gave, asks something more behavioral and comparative:\n\n> How well can the model distinguish a term from named near-neighbors before and after being given a one-sentence definition?\n\nSo the key differences are:\n\n| Concept | Main question | Unit of evaluation | Depends on context? |\n|---|---|---|---|\n| **Vocabulary coverage** | Is the term present or representable? | Term/token/type | Usually no, or only weakly |\n| **Lexical reachability** | Can the model distinguish the term from near-neighbors, and how much does a definition improve that? | Model × term × near-neighbor cell | Yes |\n\nA term can have **vocabulary coverage** but low **lexical reachability**. For example, a model may tokenize or have seen the term, but still confuse it with semantically adjacent terms. Conversely, a term may be rare or unfamiliar, but after a clear definition the model may become much better at distinguishing it from near-neighbors, yielding higher post-introduction distinguishability.\n\nIn short:\n\n> **Vocabulary coverage is about whether the word is available to the model; lexical reachability is about whether the model can behaviorally separate the term from close alternatives, especially after a definition is introduced.**",
    "**Lexical reachability** differs from **graph reachability** in both object and method.\n\n**Graph reachability** asks:\n\n> Given a graph, can one node be reached from another by following edges?\n\nIt is a structural property of a graph. For example, if there is a path from node A to node B, then B is reachable from A.\n\n**Lexical reachability**, using your canonical definition, asks:\n\n> How much does a model’s ability to distinguish a term from named near-neighbors improve after the term is introduced with a one-sentence definition?\n\nIt is a behavioral metric over model performance, not a graph-theoretic path property.\n\n| Concept | Main question | Domain | Unit of evaluation |\n|---|---|---|---|\n| **Graph reachability** | Is there a path from one node to another? | Graphs: nodes and edges | Node pair, or source-target relation |\n| **Lexical reachability** | How does definition-in-context change a model’s distinguishability of a term from near-neighbors? | Language models, terms, definitions, near-neighbor confusions | Model × term × near-neighbor cell |\n\nSo the difference is:\n\n> **Graph reachability is about connectivity in an explicit graph; lexical reachability is about the change in a model’s semantic distinguishability of a term after contextual introduction.**\n\nThey may share the word “reachability,” but they measure very different things. Graph reachability is usually binary or path-based: reachable vs. not reachable, perhaps with path length. Lexical reachability is comparative and empirical: it measures the gap between **cold-state distinguishability** and **post-introduction distinguishability**.",
    "**Lexical reachability** differs from **in-context learning capability** in scope and granularity.\n\n**In-context learning capability** is a broad ability:\n\n> Can a model use information provided in the prompt to perform better on a task, without parameter updates?\n\nIt applies to many kinds of tasks: classification, translation, reasoning, style imitation, tool use, pattern completion, and so on.\n\n**Lexical reachability**, by your canonical definition, is a specific metric:\n\n> It measures the gap between a model’s cold-state distinguishability of a term from named near-neighbors and its post-introduction distinguishability after a single-sentence definition is provided in context, scored per model × term × near-neighbor cell.\n\nSo lexical reachability is a **specialized diagnostic** of in-context lexical uptake, not the same thing as general in-context learning.\n\n| Concept | Main question | Scope | Unit of evaluation |\n|---|---|---|---|\n| **In-context learning capability** | Can the model use prompt-provided information to improve task behavior? | Broad: many tasks and formats | Model/task/example level |\n| **Lexical reachability** | Does a one-sentence definition improve the model’s ability to distinguish a term from named near-neighbors? | Narrow: term meaning and contrastive lexical discrimination | Model × term × near-neighbor cell |\n\nA model could have strong general in-context learning but still show low lexical reachability for certain terms if it cannot reliably separate the introduced term from close semantic neighbors. Conversely, a model might show good lexical reachability for a term while not being broadly strong at other forms of in-context learning.\n\nIn short:\n\n> **In-context learning capability is the general ability to learn from prompt context; lexical reachability is a targeted measure of how much a definition-in-context improves term-level distinguishability against near-neighbors.**"
  ],
  "recold_response_verbatim": "**Lexical reachability** usually means whether something—typically a variable, function, declaration, or name—is accessible from a particular point in code based on the program’s **lexical structure**: where things are written and how scopes are nested.\n\nIn simpler terms: a name is *lexically reachable* if the code at that location can “see” it according to the language’s scoping rules.\n\nExample:\n\n```js\nfunction outer() {\n  let x = 10;\n\n  function inner() {\n    console.log(x); // x is lexically reachable here\n  }\n}\n```\n\n`x` is lexically reachable inside `inner()` because `inner()` is written inside the scope where `x` is declared.\n\nBut:\n\n```js\nfunction a() {\n  let x = 10;\n}\n\nfunction b() {\n  console.log(x); // x is not lexically reachable here\n}\n```\n\nHere, `x` is not lexically reachable from `b()` because `b()` is outside the lexical scope of `a()`.\n\nThe key idea is that **lexical reachability is determined by the source code structure**, not by runtime execution paths.\n\nIt is closely related to:\n\n- **Lexical scope**\n- **Static scope**\n- **Name visibility**\n- **Closures**\n\nSo if someone says “this variable is lexically reachable,” they usually mean: “according to the nesting of scopes in the source code, this variable can be referenced from here.”",
  "recold_boundary_responses": [
    "They refer to different ideas, even though both use the word “lexical.”\n\n### 1. Lexical reachability\nIn programming, **lexical reachability** is about **scope and visibility**.\n\nIt asks:\n\n> From this point in the source code, can this name/variable/function be accessed according to the lexical scope rules?\n\nExample:\n\n```js\nfunction outer() {\n  let x = 1;\n\n  function inner() {\n    console.log(x); // x is lexically reachable here\n  }\n}\n```\n\nHere, `x` is lexically reachable inside `inner` because `inner` is written inside `outer`.\n\nSo lexical reachability is about **where a name can be referenced in code**.\n\n---\n\n### 2. Vocabulary coverage\n**Vocabulary coverage** is more common in linguistics, NLP, search, language learning, and text processing.\n\nIt asks:\n\n> How much of a text or language is covered by a given vocabulary, dictionary, model, or word list?\n\nExample:\n\nSuppose a text contains 1,000 words, and your vocabulary list recognizes 900 of them.\n\nThen the vocabulary coverage is:\n\n```text\n900 / 1000 = 90%\n```\n\nSo vocabulary coverage is about **how many words are known, recognized, or included**.\n\n---\n\n### Main difference\n\n| Concept | Main question | Field/use |\n|---|---|---|\n| **Lexical reachability** | Can this identifier/name be accessed from here? | Programming, compilers, scope analysis |\n| **Vocabulary coverage** | How much of the text is represented by this vocabulary? | NLP, linguistics, language learning |\n\n### Simple analogy\n\n- **Lexical reachability**: “Can this part of the code see that variable?”\n- **Vocabulary coverage**: “Does this vocabulary contain the words in this text?”\n\nSo, lexical reachability is about **accessibility within a structured system**, usually code, while vocabulary coverage is about **completeness of a word set relative to some text or corpus**.",
    "**Lexical reachability** and **graph reachability** are both about whether one thing can “get to” another, but they apply in different contexts and use different rules.\n\n### 1. Lexical reachability\n\n**Lexical reachability** is about **scope in source code**.\n\nIt asks:\n\n> From this location in the program text, is this variable/function/name visible according to lexical scoping rules?\n\nExample:\n\n```js\nfunction outer() {\n  let x = 10;\n\n  function inner() {\n    console.log(x); // x is lexically reachable here\n  }\n}\n```\n\n`x` is lexically reachable from `inner()` because `inner()` is written inside the scope where `x` was declared.\n\nSo lexical reachability depends on:\n\n- source-code nesting\n- block/function/module scopes\n- declarations and visibility rules\n- static/lexical structure of the program\n\nIt is not mainly about runtime paths.\n\n---\n\n### 2. Graph reachability\n\n**Graph reachability** is a graph-theory concept.\n\nIt asks:\n\n> Given a graph, is there a path from node A to node B by following edges?\n\nExample:\n\n```text\nA → B → C\n```\n\nHere, `C` is reachable from `A` because there is a path:\n\n```text\nA → B → C\n```\n\nGraph reachability depends on:\n\n- nodes\n- edges\n- direction of edges\n- existence of a path\n\nIt is used in many areas: algorithms, compilers, networks, dependency analysis, control-flow analysis, garbage collection, etc.\n\n---\n\n### Main difference\n\n| Concept | Main question | Based on |\n|---|---|---|\n| **Lexical reachability** | Can this name be referenced from here in the source code? | Lexical scope rules |\n| **Graph reachability** | Is there a path from one node to another? | Graph structure and edges |\n\n---\n\n### Important relationship\n\nLexical reachability can sometimes be **modeled using a graph**, but it is not the same thing as graph reachability.\n\nFor example, scopes can be represented as a graph/tree:\n\n```text\nglobal scope\n└── outer scope\n    └── inner scope\n```\n\nA compiler might analyze whether `inner` can access a variable in `outer` by walking through this scope structure. That can resemble graph reachability, but the meaning is specifically about **name visibility**.\n\nSo:\n\n- **Graph reachability** is a general mathematical idea.\n- **Lexical reachability** is a programming-language/scoping idea that may be implemented or analyzed using graph-like structures.",
    "**Lexical reachability** and **in-context learning capability** are very different concepts.\n\n### 1. Lexical reachability\n\n**Lexical reachability** is about whether a name is visible or accessible based on the static structure of code.\n\nIt asks:\n\n> From this point in the program, can this variable/function/declaration be referred to according to lexical scope rules?\n\nExample:\n\n```js\nfunction outer() {\n  let x = 10;\n\n  function inner() {\n    console.log(x); // x is lexically reachable here\n  }\n}\n```\n\nHere, `x` is lexically reachable inside `inner` because `inner` is written inside `outer`.\n\nSo lexical reachability is about:\n\n- source-code structure\n- nested scopes\n- variable visibility\n- static language rules\n\n---\n\n### 2. In-context learning capability\n\n**In-context learning capability** is a machine-learning/LLM concept.\n\nIt refers to a model’s ability to learn or adapt from information provided in the prompt, without changing its internal weights.\n\nIt asks:\n\n> Can the model use examples or instructions in the current context to perform a task?\n\nExample prompt:\n\n```text\nTranslate English to French.\n\ncat → chat\ndog → chien\nhouse →\n```\n\nA model with in-context learning capability may infer that:\n\n```text\nhouse → maison\n```\n\nThe model has not been retrained. It is using the examples in the prompt to infer the pattern.\n\nSo in-context learning is about:\n\n- language models\n- prompts\n- temporary task adaptation\n- using examples in the current context window\n\n---\n\n### Main difference\n\n| Concept | Main question | Domain |\n|---|---|---|\n| **Lexical reachability** | Can this name be accessed from here in code? | Programming languages, compilers |\n| **In-context learning capability** | Can a model infer and perform a task from examples in the prompt? | Machine learning, LLMs |\n\n### Simple analogy\n\n- **Lexical reachability**: “Can this part of the code see that variable?”\n- **In-context learning capability**: “Can the model figure out the task from the examples it was given?”\n\n### Key distinction\n\nLexical reachability is a **formal property of code structure**.\n\nIn-context learning capability is a **behavioral ability of an AI model**.\n\nThey can both involve “context,” but they mean very different things:\n\n- In lexical reachability, context means **surrounding scopes in source code**.\n- In in-context learning, context means **the prompt or input available to the model**."
  ],
