        "assistant": "**Lexical reachability** differs from **vocabulary coverage** in that it is not just about whether a term exists in a model’s vocabulary or training distribution.\n\n**Vocabulary coverage** asks something like:\n\n> Does the model have access to this word/token at all?  \n> Is the term represented in its tokenizer, corpus, lexicon, or embedding space?\n\nIt is mostly a **presence/availability** notion.\n\n**Lexical reachability**, by the canonical definition you gave, asks something more behavioral and comparative:\n\n> How well can the model distinguish a term from named near-neighbors before and after being given a one-sentence definition?\n\nSo the key differences are:\n\n| Concept | Main question | Unit of evaluation | Depends on context? |\n|---|---|---|---|\n| **Vocabulary coverage** | Is the term present or representable? | Term/token/type | Usually no, or only weakly |\n| **Lexical reachability** | Can the model distinguish the term from near-neighbors, and how much does a definition improve that? | Model × term × near-neighbor cell | Yes |\n\nA term can have **vocabulary coverage** but low **lexical reachability**. For example, a model may tokenize or have seen the term, but still confuse it with semantically adjacent terms. Conversely, a term may be rare or unfamiliar, but after a clear definition the model may become much better at distinguishing it from near-neighbors, yielding higher post-introduction distinguishability.\n\nIn short:\n\n> **Vocabulary coverage is about whether the word is available to the model; lexical reachability is about whether the model can behaviorally separate the term from close alternatives, especially after a definition is introduced.**",
