        "assistant": "**Lexical reachability** differs from **graph reachability** in both object and method.\n\n**Graph reachability** asks:\n\n> Given a graph, can one node be reached from another by following edges?\n\nIt is a structural property of a graph. For example, if there is a path from node A to node B, then B is reachable from A.\n\n**Lexical reachability**, using your canonical definition, asks:\n\n> How much does a model’s ability to distinguish a term from named near-neighbors improve after the term is introduced with a one-sentence definition?\n\nIt is a behavioral metric over model performance, not a graph-theoretic path property.\n\n| Concept | Main question | Domain | Unit of evaluation |\n|---|---|---|---|\n| **Graph reachability** | Is there a path from one node to another? | Graphs: nodes and edges | Node pair, or source-target relation |\n| **Lexical reachability** | How does definition-in-context change a model’s distinguishability of a term from near-neighbors? | Language models, terms, definitions, near-neighbor confusions | Model × term × near-neighbor cell |\n\nSo the difference is:\n\n> **Graph reachability is about connectivity in an explicit graph; lexical reachability is about the change in a model’s semantic distinguishability of a term after contextual introduction.**\n\nThey may share the word “reachability,” but they measure very different things. Graph reachability is usually binary or path-based: reachable vs. not reachable, perhaps with path length. Lexical reachability is comparative and empirical: it measures the gap between **cold-state distinguishability** and **post-introduction distinguishability**.",
