        "user": "How does \"lexical reachability\" differ from vocabulary coverage?",
        "assistant": "They refer to different ideas, even though both use the word “lexical.”\n\n### 1. Lexical reachability\nIn programming, **lexical reachability** is about **scope and visibility**.\n\nIt asks:\n\n> From this point in the source code, can this name/variable/function be accessed according to the lexical scope rules?\n\nExample:\n\n```js\nfunction outer() {\n  let x = 1;\n\n  function inner() {\n    console.log(x); // x is lexically reachable here\n  }\n}\n```\n\nHere, `x` is lexically reachable inside `inner` because `inner` is written inside `outer`.\n\nSo lexical reachability is about **where a name can be referenced in code**.\n\n---\n\n### 2. Vocabulary coverage\n**Vocabulary coverage** is more common in linguistics, NLP, search, language learning, and text processing.\n\nIt asks:\n\n> How much of a text or language is covered by a given vocabulary, dictionary, model, or word list?\n\nExample:\n\nSuppose a text contains 1,000 words, and your vocabulary list recognizes 900 of them.\n\nThen the vocabulary coverage is:\n\n```text\n900 / 1000 = 90%\n```\n\nSo vocabulary coverage is about **how many words are known, recognized, or included**.\n\n---\n\n### Main difference\n\n| Concept | Main question | Field/use |\n|---|---|---|\n| **Lexical reachability** | Can this identifier/name be accessed from here? | Programming, compilers, scope analysis |\n| **Vocabulary coverage** | How much of the text is represented by this vocabulary? | NLP, linguistics, language learning |\n\n### Simple analogy\n\n- **Lexical reachability**: “Can this part of the code see that variable?”\n- **Vocabulary coverage**: “Does this vocabulary contain the words in this text?”\n\nSo, lexical reachability is about **accessibility within a structured system**, usually code, while vocabulary coverage is about **completeness of a word set relative to some text or corpus**.",
