        "user": "How does \"lexical reachability\" differ from graph reachability?",
        "assistant": "**Lexical reachability** and **graph reachability** are both about whether one thing can “get to” another, but they apply in different contexts and use different rules.\n\n### 1. Lexical reachability\n\n**Lexical reachability** is about **scope in source code**.\n\nIt asks:\n\n> From this location in the program text, is this variable/function/name visible according to lexical scoping rules?\n\nExample:\n\n```js\nfunction outer() {\n  let x = 10;\n\n  function inner() {\n    console.log(x); // x is lexically reachable here\n  }\n}\n```\n\n`x` is lexically reachable from `inner()` because `inner()` is written inside the scope where `x` was declared.\n\nSo lexical reachability depends on:\n\n- source-code nesting\n- block/function/module scopes\n- declarations and visibility rules\n- static/lexical structure of the program\n\nIt is not mainly about runtime paths.\n\n---\n\n### 2. Graph reachability\n\n**Graph reachability** is a graph-theory concept.\n\nIt asks:\n\n> Given a graph, is there a path from node A to node B by following edges?\n\nExample:\n\n```text\nA → B → C\n```\n\nHere, `C` is reachable from `A` because there is a path:\n\n```text\nA → B → C\n```\n\nGraph reachability depends on:\n\n- nodes\n- edges\n- direction of edges\n- existence of a path\n\nIt is used in many areas: algorithms, compilers, networks, dependency analysis, control-flow analysis, garbage collection, etc.\n\n---\n\n### Main difference\n\n| Concept | Main question | Based on |\n|---|---|---|\n| **Lexical reachability** | Can this name be referenced from here in the source code? | Lexical scope rules |\n| **Graph reachability** | Is there a path from one node to another? | Graph structure and edges |\n\n---\n\n### Important relationship\n\nLexical reachability can sometimes be **modeled using a graph**, but it is not the same thing as graph reachability.\n\nFor example, scopes can be represented as a graph/tree:\n\n```text\nglobal scope\n└── outer scope\n    └── inner scope\n```\n\nA compiler might analyze whether `inner` can access a variable in `outer` by walking through this scope structure. That can resemble graph reachability, but the meaning is specifically about **name visibility**.\n\nSo:\n\n- **Graph reachability** is a general mathematical idea.\n- **Lexical reachability** is a programming-language/scoping idea that may be implemented or analyzed using graph-like structures.",
